Title: Los Alamos Landfill PH 2&
Description:
The current repositories cannot hold any additional material – there is no place to expand.  A third repository needs to be designed and constructed to hold a minimum of  22,000 cubic yards.  This third repository will be constructed in the former clay borrow location.  In addition, the contractor will be required to obtain all necessary clearances from the local BLM office and the current oil and gas leasee, Williams Petroleum.   This may include the relocation of associated oil and gas well appurtenances.
 The contractor will be required to:
1)  design the repository, including all restoration features, in accordance with the 100% Engineering Design Document for the Phase II Repository Expansion.  
Upon completion and final approval of the final design of Phase III, the contractor will be required to: 
2)  haul all remaining shale from the main shale pile and the north shale pile and place it in the repository and then finish constructing the repository cover per approved design requirements.  
The contractor will also be required to:
3)  construct all restoration features in the former main shale and north shale areas, including the former ponding areas and the bottom land near Sharard Gulch.  This includes all stated benching, drainage swales, diversions, and culverts to slow stormwater flow and prevent major erosion of soil from the cliffside into Sharard Gulch and to prevent damage to the access road.

Title: PG&E HBPP Decommissioning Team
Description:
1. PURPOSE
In the 2013 Nuclear Decommissioning Cost Triennial Proceeding (NDCTP) hearings, Pacific Gas and Electric Company (PG&E) Humboldt Bay Power Plant (HBPP) committed to documenting expenditures that differ from plan by ten percent (10%) or more. The compiling of the required documentation and performance of these reviews will allow PG&E to address the California Public Utilities Commission (CPU() concern regarding PG&E's performance of the Nuclear Decommissioning Project and validate whether or not it is being performed in a prudent and reasonable manner.

2. SCOPE of WORK

2.1. Mr. Valder, will report to the HBPP Director/Plant Manager and work closely with the HBPP Decommissioning Team to develop documentation needed to support PG&E's reporting obligations to the CPU( with respect to PG&E prudent utilization of Decommissioning Trust Funds.

2.2. Services shall be performed on an "as needed basis." Mr. Valder shall include the following duties in support of the Director/Plant Manager:

2.2.1. Provide Project Controls documentation of administrative and technical decisions made by HBPP in execution of the Civil Works and Self-Perform contracts that have the potential to result in changes to contract prices or the planned values by cost category that were established in various NDCTP filing documents.

2.2.2. Track modifications to the contracts and/or agreed contract scopes/specifications, as well as cost and schedule impacts, from those decisions.

2.2.3. Generate a "Master List" of decisions and contract/scope/specification modifications, updated with current status of each decision/issue each month. "No Change" updates shall be identified as such on the Master List. At a minimum, the record shall include the nature of the decision, who made the decision, factors considered, and whether and what alternatives were considered.

2.2.4. Within two (2) business days of discovery, alert the HBPP Director/Plant Manager when a decision/issue has the potential to reach a 10% impact on Project Cost, as defined by upper-level cost category in the 2012 or subsequent NDCTP filings. Within 30 days provide adequate and consistent documentation in methodologies used to support the basis of any changes from prior estimates that exceeded the+/- 10% criteria.

2.2.5. Support the Director/Plant Manager with preparation of Advice Letters, NDCTP testimony and filings, and other presentations and reports as required.

2.2.6. Provide Expert Witness testimony/support and/or attend (PUC hearings as may be requested by the Director/Plant Manager.

2.2.7. On a monthly basis, deliver an "Activity Log" identifying the actions/activities Mr. Valder is working on and any issues/opportunities/plans identified or requires support/assistance with in order to perform/complete Prudency Reviews. "No Change" updates shall be identified as such on the Activity Log.

2.2.8. Provide miscellaneous contract management and special project support, as directed by the HBPP Director/Site Manager, to the HBPP Decommissioning Manager, HBPP Decommissioning Contracts Manager, and/or HBPP Civil Works Contract Administrator.

Title: Navajo-Westwing 500kV Emergency Repair Work - Agua Fria National Monument
Description:
Navajo-Westwing 500kV Emergency Repair Work - Agua Fria National Monument
In February of 2018, damage was caused to a 1-mile long section of the static phase line of the Arizona Public Service Company (APS) Navajo-Westwing 500-2 500kV transmission line located near Black Canyon City, Yavapai County, Arizona. As a result, APS determined that emergency repairs were required to the transmission line in order to maintain operations and service to customers. Proposed construction repair activities included stringing a new static phase, removal of the damaged line, and improvement of dirt roads to enable access. Because this proposed work was scheduled to occur in the vicinity of known archaeological sites, APS and the Bureau of Land Management (BLM) requested that North Wind Resource Consulting (North Wind) provide archaeological monitoring during road improvements and work around cultural resource sites to protect sensitive resources and record any unanticipated discoveries.
This APS 500kV transmission line and associated right-of-way (ROW) cross or are in the vicinity of several previously-recorded archaeological sites located within the Agua Fria National Monument, which is managed by the BLM Phoenix District Office. The area of potential effect (APE) consists of utilized access roads and the APS 500kV transmission line ROW between APS structures 222/3 and 222/1.

Title: Midvale Class I Background Research
Description:
Class I Background Research for Midvale Telephone Company
Midvale Telephone Exchange (Midvale) proposes to install a 3.5-mile-long fiber-optic line in the City of Benson, Cochise County, Arizona. On behalf of Midvale, Monte R. Lee and Company (Monte R. Lee) contracted with North Wind Resource Consulting, Inc. (North Wind) to conduct a preliminary Class I survey to determine whether the fiber-optic alignment has previously surveyed. This information will be used to determine what areas of cultural sensitivity are located in the 3.5-mile long alignment and a 0.25-mile buffer around the alignment. 
This fiber-optic line will be located primarily underground, requiring ground disturbing activities. Proposed western portions of the alignment that cross a railroad will be constructed aboveground along previously-installed CenturyLink telecommunication poles. This activity will require no ground disturbance; however, use of a 16.5-foot construction easement, as well as a 10 foot permanent easement, will be required for routine operations and maintenance activities in the future.
The project is funded by monies from Rural Utilities Services (RUS); because Federal funds are being used, this project is considered an undertaking and is subject to Section 106 of the National Historic Preservation Act (NHPA), as amended. 
Class I information will be used by RUS to determine what portions of the alignment require Class III cultural resources inventory. Current industry standards recommend that surveys conducted within ten years of a project date and conducted in compliance with SHPO and Agency standards provide sufficient Class III coverage. Projects older than ten years are generally considered out of date with current survey standards.

Title: Repair Walls & Carpet, B654 FS#4 (HJZH 17-1211)
Description:
STATEMENT OF WORK
REPAIR WALLS AND CARPET
HJZH 17-1211
SECTION 1: PROJECT INFORMATION
1.1 PROJECT LOCATION: SABER project HJZH 17-1211 shall be completed as a routine
requirement at or near building 654 (Fire Station #4), 1st floor on Joint Base Elmendorf-
Richardson, AK. Project hours are standard work hours.
1.2 UNIQUE REQUIREMENT: None
1.3 PROJECT DESCRIPTION: Design goal for this project is to remove damaged carpet tiles
and cove base and replace with new. The inspection hole cut into wall shall be repaired,
taped, textured and painted. The area of the drinking fountain (in hallway) shall have
the drain/sewer pipe line cleaned and plugged. The drinking fountain water supply line
shall be cut and capped within the wall and an access door/panel installed.
SECTION 2: GENERAL REQUIREMENTS
2.1 WORKMANSHIP: All work shall be accomplished in accordance with all applicable
building and fire codes. Contractor shall field verify all measurements, quantities, or
value stated by the Government. Liquidated damages shall be assessed for work that is
not finished within the scheduled performance period.
2.2 WORKSITE: The contractor shall limit the work to the areas indicated by the
government. The contractor shall make every effort not to disturb or obstruct portions
of the facilities still occupied by the government. The contractor shall make efforts to
minimize interference to Government operations. The contractor shall coordinate and
schedule work with the 673 CES/CEPM office prior the start of any operation. The
contractor shall dispose of all construction debris off base at an approved disposal
facility.
2.3 SITE SECURITY AND PROTECTION: The contractor shall make every effort to secure the
work site, allowing only authorized personnel to enter the work site. The contractor
shall protect the site from damage from weather, vandalism, and/or theft.
2.4 DAMAGE TO EXISTING SITE CONDITIONS: The contractor shall be responsible to repair
any and all damage incurred to existing Real Property/Grounds due to poor
workmanship at no cost to the government. Contractor shall not park or drive on
2
sidewalk or grassy/snowy areas. Damage incurred shall be repaired at no cost to the
government.
2.5 HEALTH/SAFETY: The contractor shall be responsible for compliance with OSHA and
AFOSH standards. The contractor shall maintain a clean and debris free site at all times.
The contractor shall keep driveways and entrances into and around the work site clear
at all times. The contractor shall not use driveways or entrances as employee parking or
storage of materials unless otherwise stated. The contractor shall minimize storage of
materials and equipment on site.
2.6 GREEN PROCURMENT: Contractor must incorporate “green procurement” principles
into the design of their projects. Specifically, consult the EPA’s web site at

existing gypsum board and install new section of gypsum board to fit. Tape,

color, the entire wall section shall be painted. Standard interior/exterior paint
shall be BEHR Premium Plus: Color shall be selected by the user and approved by
the project manager.

removed shall be neatly cut to accommodate minimum 16” x 16” steel access door

Title: Install Pumps at Army Lift Station (F2212)  FTQW 18-2407
Description:
Synopsis:
Provide all labor and equipment to replace government provided pumps to Facility 2212 (Army Lift Station).
Construction:
1. Demolition:
a. Remove existing pumps and replace with government provided pumps. Demolish concrete base pad for pump and construction.
2. Construction:
a. Remove two existing pumps and replace with two government provided pumps.
i. Ensure all electrical and plumbing connections are made to new pumps installation.
ii. The contractor is responsible for any re-engineering of sole plates, pedestals, piping, and piping connections.
iii. The contractor shall connect discharge from pump to the riser and make any changes to length of the riser to ensure proper operation.
iv. The contractor shall connect inlet side and any other connections required for proper operation.
v. New pumps will need to work accordingly with existing electrical connections and operate respectively with existing electrical panel and motor control panel.
vi. Contractor will have to install one pump at a time to ensure the existing pump can/will operate while the other pump is being replaced. Additionally the contractor will not take the second pump out of service until after a 24 hour period to ensure proper operation.
vii. A base pad will most likely need to be fabricated to ensure the correct height of new pump and existing pipe align correctly.
viii. Pump 1 is currently located at Facility 1128 and will have to be moved to Facility 2212 for the install. Pump 2 is located at Facility 2212.
3. The contractor shall coordinate all hot work with the CES distribution shop representatives.
4. Contractor is responsible for all clean up and disposal of waste in and around the pump house during the project and after final operational checks.

Title: Class III Cultural Survey at Beal Lake and Cibola
Description: Class III Cultural Survey at Beal Lake and Cibola.  Beal Lake Conservation Area Expansion (Beal) and Cibola National Wildlife Refuge Expansion (Cibola) are both part of the Lower Colorado River Multi-Species Conservation Program (LCR MSCP).  The LCR MSCP is a 50-year multi-stakeholder, Federal and non-Federal partnership responding to the need to balance the use of Lower Colorado River (LCR) water resources and the conservation of native species and their habitats in compliance with the Endangered Species Act.  A goal of the LCR MSCP is to conserve and work toward the recovery of state and federally-listed species, and protect and maintain wildlife habitat along the LCR from Lake Mead to the southern international boundary with Mexico.  A major component of the LCR MSCP is the creation and management of native plant habitat; various native plant species will be established at these loci including planting of cottonwood and willow trees.
